messages.text: Investigation: Day 4
The following is an email exchange between Director Philomena Todd and Agent Falco.
The following is a transcript of an interview between Agent Falco, Deputy Decker, and Creed Keating, recorded June 23, 9:10 AM.
Good morning, Mr. Keating. Could you please state your full name and occupation for the record?
Creed Keating. I own the ice cream parlor on 6th and Main.
Scoops?
Yeah, Scoops.
So you‚Äôre Libby Dixon‚Äôs boss, correct?
Yeah. I called Lynette when Libby didn‚Äôt show up for her shift.
What was Libby like as an employee?
She was reliable, hard-working, kind of quiet.
Was it like her to call out of work or miss her shifts entirely?
No. She‚Äôs never even been late.
That‚Äôs why I was worried.
When‚Äôs the last time you saw her, Creed?
She worked the night before she disappeared. Clocked out around 6:30.
Did she seem upset or more preoccupied than usual?
Yeah, she was all teary-eyed‚Äî
Business was slow so I let her leave early.
Do you have any idea what she could‚Äôve been upset about?
I kind of just assumed it was boy troubles or something.
What makes you think that, Mr. Keating?
Libby came to work with a black eye back in March.
I heard it had to do with her boyfriend.
That sounds like more than your run-of-the-mill ‚Äúboy troubles‚Äù ‚Äî doesn‚Äôt it?
Yeah, it does. She took a short sick leave after that‚Äî
I think she was in the psych ward or whatever.
But she seemed to bounce back okay.
Bounce back?
I thought she was doing better, yeah.
I heard she broke up with her boyfriend about a month ago, I guess.
Are you referring to Duke Simmons?
I‚Äôm not naming names, Agent.
This is a missing child, Mr. Keating.
I need names.
It‚Äôs okay, Creed. We know it was Duke.
Okay, yeah. I‚Äôm talking about Duke Simmons.
He kept on coming into Scoops to check up on her, all possessive-like.
When was the last time you saw Duke at Scoops?
About a month ago, I guess. I think that‚Äôs when she dumped him.
She could‚Äôve been seeing someone new.
What makes you think so?
She seemed kind of different ‚Äî lighter, I guess.
Like a teen in love, you know?
Do you know who she might have been seeing?
No clue, Agent. She was really private about stuff like that.
Probably didn‚Äôt want her dad to know about it.
What can you tell us about Darrence Dixon?
Typical overprotective father.
He‚Äôd call sometimes to check up on her‚Äî
Make sure she was on time, ask about her work ethic, or whatever.
It was a little much, to tell you the truth.
Libby even said her dad installed some kind of tracker on her computer, too.
Did she say anything else about her Internet use?
Well, I know she asked Carter how to delete the tracking software or whatever.
She deleted the tracking software?
I guess so. Carter‚Äôs our resident computer geek, so he probably knew how to do it.
Did Libby ever seem afraid of her father?
I don‚Äôt know. I think she just needed some room to breathe.
She complained about his rules a lot.
Rules?
Well, I know she‚Äôs not allowed to have a passcode on her phone.
And he took her bedroom door off its hinges.
Excuse me?
Both hers and Anna Mae‚Äôs, actually.
Libby said he doesn‚Äôt want them doing drugs or having sex, so he took the doors off to keep an eye on them.
So where do the girls change clothes?
I don‚Äôt know ‚Äî the bathroom, I guess.
Anna Mae‚Äôs nineteen ‚Äî why doesn‚Äôt she move out?
I doubt her father would pay for that.
She could get a job, couldn‚Äôt she?
She used to clerk at the Greenwald‚Äôs across the street, but she quit without notice at the beginning of June.
How do you know she quit her job?
Lee Greenwald‚Äôs a friend of the family.
He told me he was hurting for help‚Äî
Lost two clerks in two months before Anna Mae.
Do you know why she quit so suddenly?
No, but Lee said she was really emotional.
I heard she went through a bad breakup.
Do you know anything about that, Creed?
Wasn‚Äôt she with the mechanic ‚Äî Jimmy Fitz?
I think so.
I hadn‚Äôt heard about their break-up.
Listen, I‚Äôve had about enough teen gossip, thanks to my employees.
I can imagine.
Okay, is there anything else you think we should know about Libby, Mr. Keating?
I reckon not.
Then we‚Äôll be in touch if we have any more questions, okay?
Thanks for coming in, Creed. I‚Äôll swing by for some Rocky Road soon.
I‚Äôll be expecting you, Tex.
The following is a voicemail from Agent Falco to Lynette Dixon, left June 23, 3:14 PM.
Mrs. Dixon, this is Agent Falco. I‚Äôd like to take a look at Libby‚Äôs computer, if that‚Äôs okay.
I know you said your husband installed a keystroke tracker on it, which could offer us some clues about Libby‚Äôs state of mind or personal contacts prior to her disappearance.
I hope you‚Äôre all holding up okay. Call me back when you can. Thanks so much. Bye.
The following is a text message conversation between Deputy Decker and Agent Falco, initiated June 23, 5:08 PM.
Okay, Agent, I went out to the Wired cafe like you asked. This place is a real dump.
Do they have security cameras?
Yeah, but they‚Äôre for ‚Äúlooks only.‚Äù
What the hell does that mean?
They aren‚Äôt functional.
They‚Äôre meant to scare people into behaving, I guess.
So that‚Äôs what we have to work with?
Is there some sort of sign-in sheet?
Negative.
But the clerk remembers a ‚Äútroubled young woman‚Äù coming in about twice a week.
Does the clerk have the credit card receipt?
Nope.
She paid in cash.
Well, shit.
There‚Äôs some good news, too, though.
Oh, really?
I showed Libby‚Äôs missing poster to the clerk.
Yeah, and?
He said, and I quote ‚Äî ‚ÄúYeah, that‚Äôs the broad with the big boobs.‚Äù
It‚Äôs crude, but an ID, nonetheless.
Okay, wait‚Äî
Are you telling me that ‚ÄúConnor Mason‚Äù has been positively identified by the Wired clerk as Elizabeth Dixon?
Looks like it.
Holy hell.
Yeah. So what now, boss?
